	The case of the mail routing is different, for the very purpose of the
	application is to apply relaying of messages. One could expect that
	intelligent mail routers will acquire somehow a knowledge of the "mail
	network" topology, and use that for choosing the best destination.
	After all, this is exactly what the UUCP mailer do!

Christian:

    This is precisely what MX does.  It specifies, in an abstract way,
the prefered mail path to a site.

    Your example of getting one message into France is well-taken, but
is essentially a matter of mixing mailer topology (how mailers interact)
and physical topology (how the wires are strung).  You want mailers to
know about wires so that only one copy of a message flows over a particular
wire.  Long ago, when we were designing MX, it was clear that mixing mailer
topology and physical topology didn't work very well in a fully connected
network such as the Internet -- and that we could solve 90% of our problems
using mailer topologies.  (Note too, that SMTP will send only one
copy until the last possible moment, based on MX information).

Craig

